[2]
Date: Sun 26 Jan 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Sunday Mirror, Sun 26 Jan 2003 [edited]

Scotland: Outbreaks of Undefined Illness Affect Schools in Aberdeen Area
-------------------------------------------------
Hundreds of Scots schoolchildren have been struck down by [outbreaks of
undefined illness]. Teachers fear the virus [infection] is reaching epidemic
proportions with more than 700 children developing flu-like symptoms in the
last 2 weeks in the Aberdeen area alone. At Kincorth Academy in Aberdeen,
225 children have phoned in sick in the past 2 weeks.
Headteacher Hugh Bryce, said: "We have never seen anything like this -- the
[virus] is spreading like wildfire. "About 30 percent of the pupils have
been off within the past 2 weeks and it just seems to be getting worse."
Teaching staff have also been struck down with the virus, and dozens of
supply teachers have had to be drafted into schools to provide cover.
Assistant Head Jenny Cranna at the city's Torry Academy, which has had up to
70 children a day missing, said: "It is difficult to find supply teachers
when everyone is looking for the same thing for the same reasons. "There
have been some classes which are almost empty. A lot of pupils have come to
school, but have had to be sent home because they are too ill."
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[In this area, and elsewhere, many schools are dependent on supply teachers
(called substitute teachers in the US) for maintenance of their normal
commitments throughout the year. The relative availability of supply
teachers is a novel epidemiological index. It can be presumed that the
"flu-like" symptoms may be indicative of outbreaks of viral gastroenteritis
in the absence of evidence of influenza virus infection in the area. -
Mod.CP]
